    SYNOPSIS:

      Calling big oneway requests from a fast client to a slow server
      over narrow bandwidth (simulated with small socket buffers) causes
      the client to deadlock.  Client remains deadlocked even after the
      server has caught up.

    DESCRIPTION:

      Here's the README from the attached test:

/**

@page Slow_Receiver Test README File

    This is a very simple test for TAO to demonstrate how a slow
    receiver (server) and narrow bandwidth can cause a sender
    (client) to deadlock.  It is based on the simple Hello test in
    TAO but adds a oneway operation that takes a sequence of longs.

    The client invokes this oneway operation in a for loop for
    <iteration> times passing it a sequence of longs of length
    <num_longs>.

    The server is made much slower than the client by sleeping for
    one second upon receiving each request.

    The test demonstrates the problem best when the client and
    server are running on two different nodes on a network--the
    slower the network, the better.  Nevertheless, a run_test.pl
    script is provided that will run the test on the same host, but
    it may not demonstrate the problem in that configuration.

RUNNING THE TEST

    To run the test on two different nodes (PREFERRED):

    - Run the server first on one node:

$ ./server -o test.ior

    - Copy or ftp the "test.ior" file to a second node.

    - Run the client on the second node:

$ ./client -k file://test.ior

    To make the problem worse, increase the number of times the
    client invokes the oneway operation on the server using the -i
    option and increase the length of each message by increasing the
    number of longs in the sequence with the -n option:

$ ./client -k file://test.ior -i <iterations> -n <num_longs>

    To narrow the bandwidth artificially, restrict the send and recv
    socket buffer sizes using the -ORBRcvSock option on the server
    and the -ORBSndSock option on the client.  It seems to be most
    effective to set the -ORBRcvSock option to something small on
    the server side.  A value of 512 seems to work pretty well.

    For example:

$ ./server -o test.ior -ORBRcvSock 512
$ ./client -k file://test.ior -i 100 -n 1000


    To run the test using the run_test.pl script (NOT PREFERRED):

$ ./run_test.pl

    the script returns 0 if the test was successful.

EXPECTED RESULTS

    The server simply prints "Server is ready." then blocks in
    orb->run() waiting for client requests.

    The client will print "client: Calling Hello::take_sequence()"
    for each iteration through the loop.  It will start out quickly,
    then slows down, then eventually deadlocks.  "netstat -a" on the
    server node will verify that the server has "drained down" its
    TCP receive buffer, but "netstat -a" on the client node will
    show that bytes remain in the client's TCP send buffer.

    For example (on client node):

$ netstat -a
Active Internet connections (servers and established)
Proto Recv-Q Send-Q Local Address           Foreign Address         State

... (stuff not of interest)

tcp        0  69504 xi.ociweb.com:43828     vivaldi.ociweb.co:39333 ESTABLISHED
              ^^^^^

    If the client makes it through the loop without deadlocking, it
    calls a shutdown operation on the server and the server will
    eventually exit after processing all the requests.

*/


    REPEAT BY:

      See the attached test that is adapted from the Hello test
      (attached filename: Slow_Receiver.tar.gz).

      I have only tested this on Linux (RH 7.2->RH 6.2).  I included
      Borland Makefiles, VC++ project/workspace files, and an MPC file,
      but I haven't tried to build it yet on other platforms.

    SAMPLE FIX/WORKAROUND:

      I could probably use the RelativeRoundtripTimeout policy in the
      client to timeout on the sends, reconnect to the server, and start
      sending again.  But, that would cause loss of messages and a
      resource leak.

      What would be cool would be to have some sort of policy to
      "throttle" the client until the server catches up.  I thought that
      would happen with the outgoing message queueing in
      tao/Transport.cpp.  The client does slow down for awhile, but then
      it deadlocks.

